    "comment": "Rationale: Fig.1: \"α-Actinin-1 CH1, CH2, and EF-Hand Domains Interact with PSD-95\"\nFig.2: \"α-Actinin KD Reduces Synapse Density and Postsynaptic PSD-95 Content\"\nFig.6: \"Molecular Replacement of α-Actinin with α-Actinin-1E53K or α-Actinin-1ED213,217KK and of PSD-95 with PSD-95K10E and PSD-95K11E Impairs Synaptic Localization of PSD-95 and AMPARs\"\nFig.7: \"NMDA-Induced Ca2+ Influx Causes Disruption of the PSD-95-α-Actinin Interaction by Ca2+/CaM\"\nFigure S2. \"Knockdown of α-actinin reduces spine density without influencing the morphology of\ndendrites and spines\". Experimental description: - \"Dissociated hippocampal cultures were prepared from E18 embryonic rats of both sexes.\"\n- Species of over-expressed ACTN1 is not stated in the publication. The authors were contacted for additional information (dd 16/3/2018, jwhell@ucdavis.edu). Answer:\n\n\"Dear Pim,\n\nThe ACTN1 cDNA is of human origin (originally cloned here: Edlund et al Cell Motil Cytoskeleton. 2001 Mar . 48(3):190-200.).\n\nIn case this is relevant for your database: please note that our paper does not show plain overexpression of ACTN1 but features \"molecular replacement\" by simultaneously knocking down ACTN1, ACTN2, and ACTN4.\n\nBest\n\nLucas\"",
